    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "When accessing element from typed container I am getting:\n\n```c\n  /* \"b.pyx\":9\n *     # nas = NameAssignment() #2\n *     cdef list[NameAssignment] a = []\n *     a[0] = nas             # <<<<<<<<<<<<<<\n *     b: NameAssignment = nas[0]\n*/\n  __pyx_t_1 = __pyx_v_nas;\n  __Pyx_INCREF(__pyx_t_1);\n  if (!(likely(((__pyx_t_1) == Py_None) || likely(__Pyx_TypeTest(__pyx_t_1, __pyx_mstate_global->__pyx_ptype_1b_NameAssignment))))) __PYX_ERR(0, 9, __pyx_L1_error)\n  if (unlikely((__Pyx_SetItemInt(__pyx_v_a, 0, __pyx_t_1, long, 1, __Pyx_PyLong_From_long, 0, 1, 1, __Pyx_ReferenceSharing_OwnStrongReference) < 0))) __PYX_ERR(0, 9, __pyx_L1_error)\n  __Pyx_DECREF(__pyx_t_1); __pyx_t_1 = 0;\n\n  /* \"b.pyx\":10\n *     cdef list[NameAssignment] a = []\n *     a[0] = nas\n *     b: NameAssignment = nas[0]             # <<<<<<<<<<<<<<\n*/\n  __pyx_t_1 = __Pyx_GetItemInt(__pyx_v_nas, 0, long, 1, __Pyx_PyLong_From_long, 0, 1, 1, __Pyx_ReferenceSharing_FunctionArgument); if (unlikely(!__pyx_t_1)) __PYX_ERR(0, 10, __pyx_L1_error)\n  __Pyx_GOTREF(__pyx_t_1);\n  if (!(likely(((__pyx_t_1) == Py_None) || likely(__Pyx_TypeTest(__pyx_t_1, __pyx_mstate_global->__pyx_ptype_1b_NameAssignment))))) __PYX_ERR(0, 10, __pyx_L1_error)\n  __pyx_v_b = ((struct __pyx_obj_1b_NameAssignment *)__pyx_t_1);\n  __pyx_t_1 = 0;\n```\n\nI think that call to `__Pyx_TypeTest()` when element is read can be avoided since we are validating types in container when setting item. Hence the second call to `__Pyx_TypeTest()` can be avoided in the example.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> we are validating types in container when setting item\n> the second call to `__Pyx_TypeTest()` can be avoided in the example\n\nThat's a bold assumption. First, this can only ever work for builtin container types because user defined containers may return arbitrary objects on item getting. And then, what if there are concurrent external assignments that change the item that we just put in? How do we know that no external code can access the container? What if a line tracer changes its content under our feet while we look at it?\n\nWe may decide that we trust user provided item type declarations and avoid the item type check, but it's not a safe bet per se.",
